Pedal groove and mantle cavity.
The pedal pit is large and eversible (
Figure 3B
). Large, darkly staining pedal glands are associated with the pedal pit (
Figure 4B, C
). Small sole glands similar in appearance to the pedal glands (but more darkly stained) are associated with the foot. The foot in fixed specimens consists of a single fold (
Figure 4B, C
). The mantle cavity lacks respiratory papillae (
Figure 4D
). No adhesive glands (such as that of 

Meiomenia

) were observed but there are glandular cells in the posterior mantle rim (not shown). The mantle cavity has a tubular ventral pouch, which at its muscular end holds a paired group of about 30– 40 abdominal spicules. This pouch is projectable and the whole organ could be called a genital cone (
Figure 4D
; see below).
